         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve"><head>Translations</head>
            <div type="translation" source="#jmr-jbwp-rgg2003" xml:lang="en"><p>
            <note>i</note> (Cross) Lord, help Januarius.
             <note>ii</note> Help, Lord, the Rabbi.
            <note>iii</note> Lord, help Anastasius, the man who has the doves.</p></div>
            </div>
       
         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>ii. The word is clearly Rabbi; what is less clear is how it would be understood. P.W.van der Horst, <title>Journal of Jewish Studies</title> 38 (1987) 102-106, 
            (whence <title>SEG</title> 37.1702) considers that this text can only be Jewish; it is only i that is unequivocally Christian.</p>
            <p>iii: Oliverio proposed a reference to the Emperor Anastasius; but Roussel suggested that Anastasios was a pigeon-seller.
               Robert provided an assembly of evidence for these and other bird-sellers.
              Anastasios was not selling birds to eat, but more probably as pets.
              The texts marked the place where he practised his trade.
            </p>
         </div>
         
